The paper deals with the problem of estimating unknown sparsity in compressed sensing, which is a fundamental problem in information theory (cs.IT), machine learning (cs.LG), signal processing (cs.SP), numerical analysis (cs.NA), and multimedia (cs.MM). The paper proposes a new deconvolution-based method for estimating sparsity, which has wider applicability and sharper theoretical guarantees than previous methods. The paper also discusses connections to basis pursuit denoising, the Lasso, deterministic measurement matrices, and inference problems in compressed sensing, which are all relevant to these sub-categories.
